Today is International Human Rights Day.

Human Rights Day is observed every year on 10 December. It commemorates the day on which, in 1948, the United Nations General Assembly adopted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. 

This year, Human Rights Day calls on everyone to stand up for someone's rights! Disrespect for basic human rights continues to be wide-spread in all parts of the globe. Extremist movements subject people to horrific violence. Messages of intolerance and hatred prey on our fears. Humane values are under attack.

We must reaffirm our common humanity. Wherever we are, we can make a real difference. In the street, in school, at work, in public transport; in the voting booth, on social media.

status_message:
So much of Martin Luther King Jr.'s "The Other America" speech still holds true today:

"I think America must see that riots do not develop out of thin air. Certain conditions continue to exist in our society which must be condemned as vigorously as we condemn riots. But in the final analysis, a riot is the language of the unheard. And what is it that America has failed to hear? It has failed to hear that the plight of the Negro poor has worsened over the last few years. It has failed to hear that the promises of freedom and justice have not been met. And it has failed to hear that large segments of white society are more concerned about tranquility and the status quo than about justice, equality, and humanity. And so in a real sense our nation's summers of riots are caused by our nation's winters of delay. And as long as America postpones justice, we stand in the position of having these recurrences of violence and riots over and over again. Social justice and progress are the absolute guarantors of riot prevention." - Martin Luther King, Jr. (1967)
link_name: Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. at Stanford - "The other America" 1967

Chile has just contracted for the cheapest unsubsidized power plant in the world.

In last week's energy auction, Chile accepted a bid from Spanish developer Solarpack Corp. Tecnologica for 120 megawatts of solar at the stunning price of $29.10 per megawatt-hour (2.91 cents per kilowatt-hour or kwh). This beats the 2.99 cents/kwh bid Dubai received recently for 800 megawatts. Clinton Alford Jr. was riding his bicycle home in South Los Angeles when a car pulled up behind him with the driver ordering him to stop. The driver did not identify himself as a police officer. Alford started running after he felt the back of his bicycle grabbed. Officers then used a taser to subdue him and then when Alford did not resist, handcuffed him. It was then that LAPD Officer Richard Garcia got out of his vehicle and began kicking him in the head. Garcia then leaned one knee into the small of Alford's back while placing his other knee on Alford's neck. 

After losing consciousness and a filling during the assault, Alford's limp body was carried into the back of patrol car by the callous officers. 

http://www.nationofchange.org/2016/08/11/lapd-officer-receives-community-service-beating-handcuffed-man-unconscious/

Unfortunately these instances of police brutality, especially against black men, are all too common. Many times the victim isn't lucky enough to live.

Please SHARE and LIKE if you believe that we need serious police reform.

status_message:
If your night and morning have been anything like ours, you've been devastated by the emerging news.

Within 24 hours, Alton Sterling, a 37 year old black man, was shot and killed by police in Baton Rouge. Philando Castile was shot and killed by police officers outside of Minneapolis in front of his fiancée for the apparent crime of reaching for his license and registration.

Philando's fiancée, Diamond Reynolds tearfully told reporters how he was, "a good man, a 35 year old man. Worked for a public school. Never been fingerprinted. Never been handcuffed. He has been taken away from his community. No one deserves this. I have not been to sleep, eat, work, and hold my daughter."

For many activists like us, enough was enough. Peaceful demonstrations were planned across the country from New York to Los Angeles. Times Square seemed as full as you might expect on New Year's Eve. In Dallas, a peaceful demonstration parade wrapped through the streets ending in downtown.

That's when a sniper ambush targeting police began, with gunshots killing five officers and creating pandemonium in the crowd. Amateur journalists documented the chaos live with streaming social media apps as thousands watched the violence escalate even further.

There is a real sickness in our country. Lies and denial can't salve it. Many with privilege don't want to face it. 

We have an American duty to stand up and face this injustice head on. Last night was a wake up call for the rest of the country, and we are dedicated to doing our part. We must channel our despair into positive action, our disgust into dedication, our anger into compassion.

Unfortunately the events of last night will likely drive each camp further into their own positions. It will be our task to help to overcome the fear and hatred from the right and find some common, human understanding.

Thank you for all that you do.

Donna Luca,
President of NationofChange

If you're been following this primary season as carefully as we have, you probably feel as outraged and disgusted as we do with the establishment's dirty tricks.

From large-scale voter suppression, to the media spinning the delegate totals and actually calling races early, to the statistical virtual impossibility of pro-Hillary exit polling, this election cycle has been a crash-course in US corruption.

Chicago Protesters have blocked off streets in Chicago in their efforts to demand Mayor Emanuel resign.

Many of the protesters demonstrated outside the City Council Chambers where Mayor Rahm Emanuel was addressing a special session of the City Council.

The Mayor and his administration are under fire among allegations of misconduct in the Chicago Police Department following the death of 17-year-old Laquan McDonald.

The allegations have already resulted in the resignations of the superintendent of the Chicago Police Department and the head of the Independent Police Review Authority as well as an investigation being launched of the Chicago PD. Still, many are not satisfied and want additional changes to prevent what is being called "disrespect and murder" in the community.

status_message:
Dear readers,

We are happy to announce that NationofChange.com is available again. We apologize for the inconvenience.

The reason the site was down was do to the nature of our web hosting. Currently NationofChange is on a shared server, meaning our site is hosted on a machine that also hosts other sites. The reason is cost effectiveness.

To avoid down time like this in the future, NationofChange would like to move to a dedicated server where we have a machine dedicated to our site and no others, but the expense is more than we can currently afford.

However, if we gain enough Sustaining Members (readers who commit to a $1 or more monthly donation) we will eventually be able to move to a dedicated server and avoid these down times.

If you are interested in learning more about Sustaining Membership, check out this link: https://secure.nationofchange.org/donate/?type=monthly

Thank you for being a part of NationofChange.

status_message:
Our thoughts and hearts go out to the people of Baltimore today after yesterday's violence and destruction.

We hope you can understand us when we say that we cannot condone violence of any kind; however, we do support the reasons behind these protests — we have made our stance clear since the death of Michael Brown one year ago — and we will continue to support them. Black Lives Matter.

Yesterday's actions were a direct result of the outrageous violations of human rights by our own police and justice system, the latest chapter in the centuries-old story of the chronic mistreatment of our black community by those who should protect them. Things must change, but they can't if we remain silent.

We sincerely hope that there will be national discussion and radical changes in response to these movements, and we will be there, spreading awareness for this critical issue, every step of the way.

If you would like to follow our live coverage: Protesting the Rise of the American Police State, please click here: http://goo.gl/h4UT9G
link_name: Live Coverage: Protesting the Rise of the American Police State

Now they, the Business Roundtable, and the National Association of Manufacturers, have joined together to try to discredit the purpose of disclosure policies and the advocates calling for them.
